Collecting, processing and analysing large GPS and smartphone datasets: Practical

Dr Adrian Ellison and Dr Richard Ellison
14th April, 2015

The Database

PostgreSQL database with PostGIS extensions. Contains both a GPS dataset and some Open Street Maps data.

Connection details on wireless network for this workshop:

  • IP address: 10.3.3.102
  • Database name: gisruk
  • Username: gisruk
  • Password: kursig

The Tables

Six tables in the database:

  • gpsdata – Contains the example GPS dataset
  • planet_osm_line – Contains OSM lines from area around GPS data
  • planet_osm_point – Same as above except points
  • planet_osm_polygon – Same as above except polygons
  • planet_osm_roads – Same as above except roads
  • spatial_ref_sys – Table containing the details of the projected coordinate systems

The Dataset

GPS data being used for this practical comes from a dataset collected by the University of California Berkeley using GPS chips in smartphones on the 8th of February, 2008.

Full description of the data is available in Herrera, J.C., et al. (2009) “Evaluation of traffic data obtained via GPS-enabled mobile phones: The Mobile Century field experiment”, Transportation Research Part C, doi:10.1016/j.trc.2009.10.006.

Full dataset can be downloaded from: http://traffic.berkeley.edu/project/downloads/mobilecenturydata

GPS data

The gpsdata table contains the following fields:

  • obsid – Unique ID for each observation
  • obstime – Timestamp (without timezone) for each observation
  • lat – Latitude of observation
  • lng – Longitude of observation
  • spd – Point speed of travel at observation
  • heading – Direction (based on average of three previous points), in degrees from 0° to 360°
  • latlng – Spatial field using SRID 4326 (WGS84 for GPS)
  • vehid – ID of vehicle/device

GPS data and SQL

Analysing very large datasets, including those of GPS and smartphone data relies extensively on the use of the database and SQL to calculate basic statistics and subset data.

Why?

  • Make use of database indices to speed up retrieval, calculations
  • Can not load hundreds of millions of records without crashing most (all?) statistical software
  • Databases have been optimised for performing lookups on very large datasets
  • PostGIS-enabled queries are substantially faster than many GIS software packages.

GPS data, SQL and R

  • Load RPostgreSQL library so that we can connect to the database
library("RPostgreSQL")
  • Specify the database type
drv <- dbDriver("PostgreSQL")

GPS data, SQL and R

  • Connect to the database. Since we're connecting to a server on another computer with a different username and password, we need to specify these.
  • Otherwise we would only need to specify the database name (dbname)
con <- dbConnect(drv, dbname="gisruk", host="10.3.3.102", user="gisruk", password="kursig")
  • We run a small query to make sure it works and output the result to the rs (resultset) data frame
rs <- dbGetQuery(con,"SELECT * FROM gpsdata LIMIT 10")

GPS data, SQL and R

  • You will notice a warning message about the field type geometry being unrecognised
  • This is because the postgis field types are not recognised by the DBI driver we are using
  • This can be ignored because the field it is referring to is only used within the query and this is processed by PostgreSQL/PostGIS itself

GPS data, SQL and R

  • To get a feel for the data, lets just see how many observations there are per vehicle and the average speed
  • In PostgreSQL count(*) can be quite slow unless it is run on a field with an index
rs <- dbGetQuery(con,"SELECT vehid, count(*) as numobs, avg(spd) as avgspd, stddev_pop(spd) as sdspd FROM gpsdata GROUP BY vehid")

GPS data, SQL and R

  • The average speed that is calculated here is not actually the average speed.
  • It is the average of the speed recorded at the time of each observation.
  • If the interval between observations varies or is too far apart (>1 second), you would need to determine the elapsed time between consecutive points, calculate the distance and use those values to determine a speed between observations.
  • Only then could you calculate an average speed.
  • For our purposes in this workshop we'll assume that this is the 'true' average speed.

GPS data, SQL and R

  • Load the ggplot2 library so we can plot the average speeds
library("ggplot2")

GPS data, SQL and R

  • Plot the average speed and the standard deviation of the speeds for each vehicle
ggplot(rs, aes(x=factor(vehid),y=avgspd,fill=sdspd)) + geom_bar(stat="identity")

GPS data, SQL and R

  • Most vehicles seem to have an average speed of between 25 and 35 miles/hour but some are below that with quite a small standard deviation which is unusual in a driving situation which (usually) requires some acceleration and braking behviour
  • We can look at a specific place and look at how many vehicles were doing above/below a certain speed
  • We can run a query that pulls the individual observations for these vehicles

GPS data, SQL and R

  • Find the vehicle IDs of vehicles that travelled above 75 mph on a specific piece of the motorway:
fastloc <- dbGetQuery(con,"SELECT DISTINCT vehid FROM gpsdata, planet_osm_roads WHERE ST_DWithin(ST_Transform(way, 4326), latlng, 0.00001) AND highway='motorway' AND spd > 75 AND osm_id = 98969782 ORDER BY vehid LIMIT 10000;")

GPS data, SQL and R

  • svid has five observations: 171,156,110,123,165
  • Usually we wouldn't do it this way because there could be hundreds of vehicles that would be included.
slowvehs <- dbGetQuery(con,"SELECT obsid,lat,lng,spd,heading,vehid FROM gpsdata WHERE vehid IN (171,156,110,123,165)")

GPS data, SQL and R

  • Now we have the observations we can look at more detail at these observations
ggplot(slowvehs, aes(x=spd, colour=factor(vehid), group=factor(vehid))) + geom_density()

GPS data, SQL and R

  • Seems quite similar to each other (although there are differences)
  • How does this compare with the faster vehicles?
  • Get the raw data (this may take a while)
fastvehs <- dbGetQuery(con,"SELECT obsid,lat,lng,spd,heading,vehid FROM gpsdata WHERE vehid NOT IN (171,156,110,123,165)")

ggplot(fastvehs, aes(x=spd,colour=factor(vehid),group=factor(vehid))) + geom_density()

GPS data, SQL and R

GPS data, SQL and R

  • Quite a different pattern - question is why?

  • Lets do a spatial density plot by speed and slow/fast vehicles

  • Bin speeds first

slowvehs$spdbins <- .bincode(slowvehs$spd, c(0,20,40,60,80,100), right = TRUE, include.lowest = FALSE)
fastvehs$spdbins <- .bincode(fastvehs$spd, c(0,20,40,60,80,100), right = TRUE, include.lowest = FALSE)

GPS data, SQL and R

  • Then plot based on lat/long and speed bin
ggplot() + stat_density2d(
  data=slowvehs,
  aes(x=lng, y=lat, colour=factor(spdbins), fill=factor(spdbins), alpha = ..level.. ),
  size = 1,
  bins = 5,
  geom = "polygon")

Final comments

  • Large GPS and smartphone datasets require some selection in what data is used when plotting
  • Whenever possible, utilise the functionality of the database to analyse, preprocess or subset data before importing into R (or other software)
  • Sometimes necessary to split data into logical subsets for individual analysis – e.g., only one person, vehicle, road or day
